ce":"wiktextract","senses":[{"pos":"noun","gloss":"bridge"},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to arch, to vault (a bridge)","tags":["transitive"]},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to span, to traverse, to cross (as if by a bridge)","tags":["transitive"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"verbal noun of جَسَرَ (jasara) (form I)","tags":["form-of","noun-from-verb","transitive"]},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to dare, to risk, to venture","tags":["transitive"],"examples":[{"text":"لَا يَجْسُرُ أَنْ يَفْعَلَ كَذَا.","english":"He dares not do such a thing."}]},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to act boldly or courageously","tags":["transitive"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"Jessore (a city in Bangladesh)","tags":["transitive"]}]},"etymology":{"source":"wiktextract","text":"From Aramaic גִּישְׁרָא / גִּשְׁרָא (gišrā) / ܓܫܪܐ (gešrā), with Hebrew גֶּשֶׁר (géšer) from Akkadian 𒄀𒅖𒊒 (gišru, “bridge”). Note the meaning “timber, beam” in Syriac – originally the Arabic word meant a wooden bridge in distinction from a stone bridge قَنْطَرَة (qanṭara). The word has a derivation in Akkadian from 𒄑𒃡 (GIŠ.ÙR), 𒄑𒃡𒋗 (GIŠ.ŠU.ÙR /⁠gušūru, gašūru⁠/, “tree-trunk; felled log, timber; beams”), itself considered a Sumerian loanword.\n\nDenominal verb of جِسْر (jisr, “bridge”).\n\nBorrowed from Classical Persian جَسَر (jasar), from Bengali যশোর (jośōr)."},"ipa":["/d͡ʒisr/","/d͡ʒa.sa.ra/","/d͡ʒasr/","/d͡ʒa.sar/"]}